<font color="#FF0000">A LITTLE HUMILITY, NOT LIKE ME</font><br>
<tt>Tue Feb 11 23:16:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Sometimes you can walk into a conversation and think you<br>
know what you have heard, but you haven't. You have just<br>
heard what you heard.<br><br>
To anyone I have offended. I apologize. I can see that<br>
I will need to go back and review what has transpired to<br>
date to see what's going on here. It kinda feels like the<br>
group sessions we had. When you walked in the door, you<br>
could not help but be defensive. They could not help but<br>
be superior. It's the nature of group interaction.<br><br>
I am and have always been willing to share my experience<br>
and my opinions. It got me to surviving. The honest feed<br>
back it always caused was a fantastic mirror. I request<br>
time to check this out. My initial posting came from first<br>
impressions and perhaps my mood.<br><br>
In the almost exactly 30 years I have had to deal with what<br>
Vietnam was and is to me, I only know one thing. It lives<br>
in my heart, intellect, and hopes. I cannot and will not<br>
stop exploring it, or else I get to stop right there where<br>
I was.<br><br>
You get angry with me, I get angry with you. I have no airs<br>
to project. I have nothing to defend about my feelings or<br>
anything that ever happened to me there. Not anymore. All<br>
I ask is patience, and a little slack. I will be agressive,<br>
but expect the same in return. Otherwise, I have found you<br>
give us Vets an intellectual avenue of escape. The same one<br>
that got our own heads in trouble.<br><br>
Give me your feedback. I need it, and always will till I'm<br>
back home with the buddies that haunt me.<br><br>
See Ya,<br>

